title: Fission studies in the reaction of 19F with 209Bi at 99.2 MeV

x4freetext: Fission studies in the reaction of 19F with 209Bi
at 99.2 MeV

x4codes.hlp: Bhabha Atomic Research Centre (BARC), Trombay, Mumbai, India

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Journal of Radioanalytical and Nuclear Chemistry, Vol.279, p.547 (2009)

x4codes.hlp: Tata Institute of Fundamental Research, Mumbai, India

x4freetext: Pelletron Accelerator (14 MV Tandem
accelerator)
Targets of super pure 209Bi (0.84 mg/cm2 thick) were
prepared by vacuum evaporation on 7.6 micro-meter super
pure aluminium foil.
The fission products were collected on 25.4 micro-meter
thick aluminum foil by recoil catcher technique.
The whole assembly was put in a target holder and
irradiated for a suitable length of time with 100 MeV
19F particle beam of ~100 nano-ampere.
Average incident energy of 19F on the bismuth targets
was 99.2 MeV.
Four irradiations were carried out for
varying duration of time from around 2 and 12 hours so
as to cover both the short and long lived fission
products.
The decay of the activity for the fission
products was followed from a few minutes to a few days
for the short irradiations and from a few hours to
10 days for the longer irradiations.
The cumulative production cross section was determined
for most of the mass chains. In case of shielded nuclei
independent production cross section was determined.
Fission product yield studies in the reaction of
99.2 MeV 19F with 209Bi have been carried out using
gamma-ray spectrometry. Cross sections for the
production of fission products have been determined.
Yield distribution of fission products was found to be
symmetric and broad with FWHM around 22 mass units and
peak near mass 111. The average number of neutrons
emitted per fission has been found to be around 6.7.
Comparison of the fission products yield distribution
of 209Bi using projectiles like 4He, 12C, 16O, and 19F
have shown that the mass of symmetric peak increases as
the mass of the compound nucleus increases.
High fission yield around mass 112 has been attributed
to the presence of deformed neutron shells.
Total fission cross section and width of the mass
distribution have been found to be low in case of 16O
induced fission as compared to the 4He, 12C, and 19F
induced fission of 209Bi.

product, the above mentioned FCY in the true sense is a
relative fractional cumulative yield (RCY).

x4freetext: Measured independent and cumulative cross sections
of the given fission products was used to arrive
at the total chain yield (YA). The independent yield
and cumulative yield of a fission product in a given
mass chain was assumed to be in the Gaussian form.
In the absence of data on the width of the distribution
(Sz) and most probable charge (Zp), the Zp was
determined assuming unchanged charge distribution
(UCD). Since, neither the data on Sz nor on average
number of neutrons emitted per fission (vT) was
available for 209Bi(19F,f), hence these were determined
by fitting the experimental yields to the equations in
an iterative manner.
An average value of vT was assumed and the YA for the
fission products was determined. Calculated YA was
used to arrive at the new vT value. The input and
calculated vT were compared. The input vT value was
varied between 5 to 10 to arrive at the appropriate
value of vT. This whole process was repeated for
various Sz values from 0.8 to 1.1. YA were compared for
all these Sz values to arrive at the best fit.
The input value of vT = 6.7 for 99.2 MeV gave the best
fit for the YA distribution at  Sz = 0.90.

but in fact it should be CHN instead of CUM, as this
is a chain yield cross section
